</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="91FC40A8A76C2D2A94F302C4A816C37D" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="47C717D4BF325490875B70FBEC5A2B5C" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A6F7026CD2E3E9C4F0A652C9CCC85A5" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">The specific name refers to the arrangement of the five dark markings on the forewing arranged radially in the form of a flower.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="56256EB2FDF9623C914DD0BC665E34F8" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="note">
<paragraph id="D54F73F6A49DA6EEBC3DCA13C5FF108E" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<pageBreakToken id="2046C4E3940FAAFF403EE6EAFD6BE667" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" start="start">Note</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6DCFB5AB009054DD5CABFEE41A701703" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
This species closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="093F736ECE139C7BB4B8138995A2D7B3" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Balera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Balera bracata" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bracata">Balera bracata</taxonomicName>
but has a short process on the pygofer and the aedeagus is wider with the apical bifurcation shorter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
